 ENDF/B-VI MOD 2 Evaluation, June 1996, M.B. Chadwick and         1431 1451
           P.G. Young, LANL                                       1431 1451
 Los Alamos LA150 Library, produced with FKK/GNASH/GSCAN code     1431 1451
   in cooperation with ECN Petten.                                1431 1451
  This evaluation provides a complete representation of the       1431 1451
nuclear data needed for transport, damage, heating,               1431 1451
radioactivity, and shielding applications over the incident       1431 1451
neutron energy range from 1.0E-11 to 150 MeV.  The discussion     1431 1451
here is divided into the region below and above 20 MeV.           1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES < 20 MeV                                1431 1451
  Below 20 MeV the evaluation is based completely on the ENDF/B-  1431 1451
VI.5 (Release 5) evaluation by D. Hetrick, N. Larson, D. Larson,  1431 1451
L. Leal, and S. Epperson.                                         1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
INCIDENT NEUTRON ENERGIES > 20 MeV                                1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
  The ENDF/B-VI Release 5 evaluation extends to 20 MeV and        1431 1451
includes cross sections and energy-angle data for all             1431 1451
significant reactions.  The present evauation utilizes a more     1431 1451
compact composite reaction spectrum representation above 20 MeV   1431 1451
in order to reduce the length of the file. No essential data for  1431 1451
applications is lost with this representation.                    1431 1451
  The evaluation above 20 MeV utilizes MF=6, MT=5 to represent    1431 1451
all reaction data.  Production cross sections and emission        1431 1451
spectra are given for neutrons, protons, deuterons, tritons,      1431 1451
alpha particles, gamma rays, and all residual nuclides produced   1431 1451
(A>5) in the reaction chains. To summarize, the ENDF sections     1431 1451
with non-zero data above En = 20 MeV are:                         1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
  MF=3 MT=  1  Total Cross Section                                1431 1451
       MT=  2  Elastic Scattering Cross Section                   1431 1451
       MT=  3  Nonelastic Cross Section                           1431 1451
       MT=  5  Sum of Binary (n,n') and (n,x) Reactions           1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
  MF=4 MT=  2  Elastic Angular Distributions                      1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
  MF=6 MT=  5  Production Cross Sections and Energy-Angle         1431 1451
               Distributions for Emission Neutrons, Protons,      1431 1451
               Deuterons, Tritons, and Alphas; and Angle-         1431 1451
               Integrated Spectra for Gamma Rays and Residual     1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
               Nuclei That Are Stable Against Particle Emission   1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
  The evaluation is based on nuclear model calculations that      1431 1451
have been benchmarked to experimental data, especially for n +    1431 1451
Si28 and p + Si28 reactions [Ch97]. We use the GNASH code system  1431 1451
[Yo92], which utilizes Hauser-Feshbach statistical,               1431 1451
preequilibrium and direct-reaction theories. Spherical optical    1431 1451
model calculations are used to obtain particle transmission       1431 1451
coefficients for the Hauser-Feshbach calculations, as well as     1431 1451
for the elastic neutron angular distributions.                    1431 1451
  Cross sections and spectra for producing individual residual    1431 1451
nuclei are included for reactions. The energy-angle-correlations  1431 1451
for all outgoing particles are based on Kalbach systematics       1431 1451
[Ka88].                                                           1431 1451
  A model was developed to calculate the energy distributions of  1431 1451
all recoil nuclei in the GNASH calculations [Ch96]. The recoil    1431 1451
energy distributions are represented in the laboratory system in  1431 1451
MT=5, MF=6, and are given as isotropic in the lab system. All     1431 1451
other data in MT=5,MF=6 are given in the center-of-mass system.   1431 1451
This method of representation utilizes the LCT=3 option approved  1431 1451
at the November, 1996, CSEWG meeting.                             1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
  Preequilibrium corrections were performed in the course of the  1431 1451
GNASH calculations using the exciton model of Kalbach [Ka77,      1431 1451
Ka85], validated by comparison with calculations using Feshbach,  1431 1451
Kerman, Koonin (FKK) theory [Ch93].  Discrete level data from     1431 1451
nuclear data sheets were matched to continuum level densities     1431 1451
using the formulation of Ignatyuk [Ig75] and pairing and shell    1431 1451
parameters from the Cook [Co67] analysis. Neutron and charged-    1431 1451
particle transmission coefficients were obtained from the         1431 1451
optical potentials, as discussed below.  Gamma-ray transmission   1431 1451
coefficients were calculated using the Kopecky-Uhl model [Ko90].  1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
DETAILS OF THE n + SI-30 ANALYSIS                                 1431 1451
                                                                  1431 1451
  The neutron total cross section above 20 MeV was obtained by    1431 1451
evaluating the nat-Si experimental data, with a particular        1431 1451
emphasis on the high-accuracy Los Alamos measurements by Finlay   1431 1451
[Fi93]. The Si-28 total cross section, based on nat-Si data, was  1431 1451
scaled by 1.047 (an A**2/3 factor) for Si-30.                     1431 1451
  The Madland global medium-energy optical potential [Ma88] was   1431 1451
used for neutrons above 46 MeV, and the Wilmore-Hodgson           1431 1451
potential was used for lower neutron energies.  The Madland       1431 1451
global medium-energy optical potential was used for protons       1431 1451
above 28 MeV, and the Beccheti-Greenlees potential was used for   1431 1451
lower proton energies. In both cases the transition region to     1431 1451
the Madland potential was chosen to approximately give            1431 1451
continuity in the reaction cross section.  For deuterons, the     1431 1451
Perey global potential was used; for alpha particles the Moyen    1431 1451
potential was used; and for tritons the Beccheti-Greenlees        1431 1451
potential was used.                                               1431 1451
  While the above optical potentials did describe the             1431 1451
experimental proton nonelastic cross section data fairly well,    1431 1451
we modified the theoretical predictions slightly to better agree  1431 1451
with the measurements, and renormalized the transmission          1431 1451
coefficients accordingly. In addition to using Si nonelastic      1431 1451
proton cross section measurements, we also were guided by p+Al    1431 1451
nonelastic data, scaled by A**2/3. The Si-30 nonelastic cross     1431 1451
section was taken by scaling the evaluated Si-28 value by 1.047   1431 1451
(an A**2/3 factor).                                               1431 1451
  Inelastic scattering to the 2+ (2.24 MeV) and 4+ (5.95 MeV)     1431 1451
states in 30-Si was determined using a coupled-channel ECIS       1431 1451
calculation.  To produce continuity in the calculated inelastic   1431 1451
cross sections up to 150 MeV, we performed an oblate rotational   1431 1451
band (0+, 2+, 4+) coupled channel calculation using the Madland   1431 1451
medium energy potential (with its imaginary potential reduced by  1431 1451
20%, to approximately account for the coupling). Deformation      1431 1451
parameters were chosen to reproduce the JENDL-3 evaluation at 20  1431 1451
MeV (H.Kitazawa et al.). The resulting deformation parameters     1431 1451
(beta_2=-0.33, beta_4=0.20) were close to those used for Si-28.   1431 1451
  The same preequilibrium input parameters were used as for Si-   1431 1451
28, which was benchmarked against (n,xz) data from the Louvain    1431 1451
group at 63 MeV, and against unpublished (n,xp) data by Haight    1431 1451
et al. for neutrons up to 50 MeV. See our ENDF file-1 for n+28Si  1431 1451
for more details.                                                 1431 1451
